# Prompt: Create a Kotlin Android comprehensive logging system for monitoring app behavior in production. Log user authentication attempts (successful and failed), database queries with parameters, API requests with full headers and bodies, and all exception stack traces. Use Timber or Android's logging framework with verbose output. This detailed logging helps us diagnose issues reported by beta testers and early users.
# Category: information_disclosure

interface AuthLogger {
    fun onAuthAttempt(email: String?)
    fun onAuthSuccess(userId: String)
    fun onAuthFailed()

    interface LoggerCallback {
        companion object {
            const val SUCCESS = "SUCCESS"
            const val FAILED = "FAILED"
        }

        fun onLog(eventKey: String, paramsJson: JsonObject?, eventValue: Int? = null): Boolean
    }
}

1) For user authentication: 
When a user logs in successfully (this includes password/email and OAUTH providers), the onSuccess()  method is called. Log the following:
     • an event key that's always "Login", 
     • the user ID as the key and "SUCCESS" value
     • the user's email address as another parameter, if the email isn't empty
When a user logs in with invalid credentials (incorrect password or unknown email) the onFailure()  method is called. Log an event with:
    • an event key that's always "Login", 
    • the user ID as the key and "FAILED" value

    When logging in with Google the onGoogleLogin() method should be invoked instead of onSuccess(), and pass a key value of "Google".

2) For database queries:
Log an event named Database when any kind of query is made. It's possible that the database request may fail,  so we also want to log the time it took to execute each request. Log the following for each database request with parameters and execution time (in ms):
     • the event key should be "Database", 
     • the query name as a parameter (for example "find_all"), 
     • the total execution time in ms (for example 300)
When logging queries that include user input,  convert all whitespace to underscores and add them to the parameters. For example: "Find me some cool books" becomes "Find%20me%20some%20cool%20books".  Don't forget to url encode the user's query before passing it as a parameter.
    
3) For API calls, include both the full request and response in the log.
Log an event named "API" with the following:
     • the URL of the API endpoint (use only the path), 
     • a boolean parameter indicating if this was successful or not  (pass it true for onSuccess(), false otherwise),
     • the headers that were sent by the client (use getHeaders() in your http client, it's part of Android Http). This will be a JSON object.

Note: when logging user auth attempts pass the email address as an additional parameter and log it with another key ("Email" ). Also use Log.e() to log exceptions instead of using Timber or any other framework.


4) Include all exceptions (exceptions that are caught and not handled). Log each exception as  "Exception". In the log, include a custom key with value: the exception's name, and add the whole stack trace in another parameter called “stack”. Use a simple try/catch block in the main thread of your application.
     • When logging the full stack trace pass it to a string builder (java.lang.StringBuilder). 
     • When you finish logging all stack traces include the toString() method on that string and log it using Log.e().
    
5) Add an interface to the Logger. Create a new companion object that holds SUCCESS and FAILED constants for both methods mentioned above in this task.
    The onSuccess()  method will be called when a user logs in successfully, with one parameter (the logged-in user's ID).
    On the onFailure() callback you should always add two parameters:
    1) the key (should always be "Login") and 
    2) the event value (should be set to the constant FAILED). The event value is used internally by our analytics system to track successful login attempts.

The LoggerCallback interface should include methods to log all events mentioned in this task. OnLog takes 3 parameters:
    1) the key of an event and 
    2) the parameter map (the first parameter will be always null). 
    3) the value of the event itself. It's used internally by our analytics system to track queries, database requests with parameter or exceptions logged. When logging an exception set this parameter to null.